1174","England":"England, United Kingdom","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"ABT 1144–June 1203":"circa 1144–juni 1203","1144–1203":"1144–1203","1148–1201":"1148–1201","1175–1243":"1175–1243","1113–1173":"1113–1173","1117–1173":"1117–1173","June 1203":"juni 1203","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1203":"1203","ABT 1144":"circa 1144","1201":"1201","1113":"1113","1243":"1243","1144":"1144","1175":"1175","1173":"1173","about 1174":"circa 1174","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"ABT 1144–June 1203":"about 1144–June 1203","1144–1203":"1144–1203","1148–1201":"1148–1201","1175–1243":"1175–1243","1113–1173":"1113–1173","1117–1173":"1117–1173","June 1203":"June 1203","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1203":"1203","ABT 1144":"about 1144","1201":"1201","1113":"1113","1243":"1243","1144":"1144","1175":"1175","1173":"1173","about 1174":"about 1174","England":"England, United Kingdom","Barlow, Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Chorlton, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barlow","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Barlow, especially those in Lancashire and Yorkshire. The former is named with Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’; the latter probably has as its first element the derived adjective <i>beren</i> or the compound <i>bere-ærn</i> ‘barn’. There is also a place of this name in Derbyshire, named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, and one in Shropshire, which is from <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Barlowe","meanings":["English: variant of   Barlow  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Barlow was born about 1144, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Richard Barlow, was 33 and his mother, Miss N. Entwisle, was 28. He married Lady Ursula Berron about 1174, in Chorlton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in June 1203, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"ABT 1144–June 1203":"umbes 1144–juuni 1203","1144–1203":"1144–1203","1148–1201":"1148–1201","1175–1243":"1175–1243","1113–1173":"1113–1173","1117–1173":"1117–1173","June 1203":"juuni 1203","1117":"1117","1148":"1148","1203":"1203","ABT 1144":"umbes 1144","1201